body:
## 🐛 Bug Report

<!-- A clear and concise description of what the bug is. -->

Lib version: 4.2.1

When exporting to Excel in an XLSX file, attempting to enable or disable the `useSharedStrings` option has no effect on the end result. The `sharedStrings.xml` file is produced and the `worksheet.xml` files still point to it.

## Steps To Reproduce

<!-- The exact steps required to reproduce the issue, ideally with a code example -->

The following code is used to create and save the workbook

```javascript
// spin up a new workbook
const workbook = new ExcelJS.Workbook();

// some amount of data processing inside here
const sheet = workbook.addWorksheet(...);

// write and save using FileSaver library
// the result is the same regardless if writeBuffer({ useSharedStrings: false }) or writeBuffer({ useSharedStrings: true }) is used below
workbook.xlsx.writeBuffer().then(data => {
    const blob = new Blob([data], { type: "application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.spreadsheetml.sheet;charset=UTF-8" });
    FileSaver.saveAs(blob, "test.xlsx");
});
```

## The expected behaviour:

<!-- A clear and concise description of what you expected to happen. -->

Per documentation, the default behavior is not to use shared strings. Either by default or when explicitly set to false, the `writeBuffer` function should not produced a `sharedStrings.xml` within the workbook.
